<div id="review_123910415" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/123910415" />
    <a title="Chrissie" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/632247-chrissie"><img alt="Chrissie" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1321799585p2/632247.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/123910415?book_show_action=true">Sep 28, 2010</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Chrissie" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Chrissie" href="/user/show/632247-chrissie">Chrissie</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=bio">bio</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=germany">germany</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=austria">austria</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=history">history</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=soviet-union">soviet-union</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=2012-read">2012-read</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=religion">religion</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=italy">italy</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=kirkus">kirkus</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=hungary">hungary</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer123910415" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15929221049836108962">This book includes the two books <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/6174.Survival_in_Auschwitz' title='Survival in Auschwitz by Primo Levi' rel='nofollow noopener'>Survival in Auschwitz</a> and <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/6175.The_Reawakening' title='The Reawakening by Primo Levi' rel='nofollow noopener'>The Reawakening</a> by Primo Levi. The American and European publications have employed different titles. The book ends with an excellent &quot;Afterword&quot;. This too is written by the author. I recommend this edition.<br/><br/>This book is quite different from other holocaust books, by its very lack of emotion. It is a clear statement of what exactly happened to the author, both in the camp (If This is a Man) and afterwards on his travels home to Turin, Ita</span>
  <span id="freeText15929221049836108962" style="display:none">This book includes the two books <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/6174.Survival_in_Auschwitz" title="Survival in Auschwitz by Primo Levi" rel="nofollow noopener">Survival in Auschwitz</a> and <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/6175.The_Reawakening" title="The Reawakening by Primo Levi" rel="nofollow noopener">The Reawakening</a> by Primo Levi. The American and European publications have employed different titles. The book ends with an excellent "Afterword". This too is written by the author. I recommend this edition.<br /><br />This book is quite different from other holocaust books, by its very lack of emotion. It is a clear statement of what exactly happened to the author, both in the camp (If This is a Man) and afterwards on his travels home to Turin, Italy (The Truce). In the "Afterword" the author answers questions that readers have repeatedly asked. His answers are clear, concise and right to the point. This is a perfect ending to the book since you see how the author reasons <u>after</u> living through the experiences described. He knew <u>exactly</u> where he stood on every question. His wisdom impressed me.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15929221049836108962" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


