<span id="freeTextContainer11076323036840024701">How can I even think that I can pass judgement on this in a literary sense? It would be wrong.<br/><br/>Quite simply the rawest and most moving book I have ever - and probably will ever - read. Not just because of the personal experiences that Primo describes, but also for the inconceivable way in which he rises above the inconceivable evil.<br/><br/>The end of the books contains a list of the questions he was often asked after writing the book and his answer that he doesn&apos;t hate Germans because that is the root of</span>
  <span id="freeText11076323036840024701" style="display:none">How can I even think that I can pass judgement on this in a literary sense? It would be wrong.<br /><br />Quite simply the rawest and most moving book I have ever - and probably will ever - read. Not just because of the personal experiences that Primo describes, but also for the inconceivable way in which he rises above the inconceivable evil.<br /><br />The end of the books contains a list of the questions he was often asked after writing the book and his answer that he doesn't hate Germans because that is the root of the evil that he endured, is incredible. A truly great man.<br /><br />An absolute must-read.</span>
