<div class='bookAuthorProfile__about'>

<span id="freeTextContainer6864734286090545300"><b>Primo Michele Levi</b> (Italian: [ˈpriːmo ˈlɛːvi]) was a chemist and writer, the author of books, novels, short stories, essays, and poems. His unique 1975 work, <i>The Periodic Table</i>, linked to qualities of the elements, was named by the Royal Institution of Great Britain as the best science book ever written.<br/><br/>Levi spent eleven months imprisoned at Monowitz, one of the three main camps in the Auschwitz c</span>
  <span id="freeText6864734286090545300" style="display:none"><b>Primo Michele Levi</b> (Italian: [ˈpriːmo ˈlɛːvi]) was a chemist and writer, the author of books, novels, short stories, essays, and poems. His unique 1975 work, <i>The Periodic Table</i>, linked to qualities of the elements, was named by the Royal Institution of Great Britain as the best science book ever written.<br /><br />Levi spent eleven months imprisoned at Monowitz, one of the three main camps in the Auschwitz concentration camp complex (record number: 174,517) before the camp was liberated by the Red Army on 18 January 1945. Of the 650 Italian Jews in his transport, Levi was one of only twenty who left the camps alive.<br /><br />The Primo Levi Center, dedicated "to studying the history and culture of Italian Jewry," was named in his honor.</span>
  <a data-text-id="6864734286090545300" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

